node.text:
On Christmas Day I’ll be dropping a full length documentary based on my experiences in 2020. This footage was captured over the course of the past year by myself and my amazing crew members, and as you’ll see here, is also narrated by me. This is definitely outside of my comfort zone, but I have some major announcements on the horizon for 2021 where you’ll be seeing both myself and my content in a whole new way (I can’t say more at this time, but it’s major!). 
I hope you enjoy this short segment and I would love to hear your feedback in the comments!

node.text:
Local San Diego is all of a sudden exploding with life! Each year as the fall arrives, so too does the giant pods of long beaked common dolphins and Humpback Whales to feed on the abundant anchovies in our waters! Yesterday was a special treat because “Twitch” the Humpback Whale made his triumphant return to La Jolla! He spent the day in classic form, following around thousands of dolphins, lunge feeding, breaching, and of course being extra friendly with our boat! Most of the day was spent in La Jolla which seems to be the zone the Humpbacks love the most during the fall, and it is certainly one of my favorite spots to take the boat! It’s the prettiest coastline in San Diego as far as I’m concerned! Who remembers when this Humpback spent a few days between the cove and the shores back in 2019!?!

Now through the next couple months is a GREAT time to book a trip with @gonewhalewatching as most of the action will be right within range of our 2.5 hour trips! See you all out there!

If you want to join me head over to www.gonewhalewatching.com to book your spot! Beautiful conditions are forecasted!

WE ADDED A SECOND WEEK OF WHALE WATCHING IN MAUI FOR 2022! DON’T MISS YOUR CHANCE AT THE TRIP OF A LIFETIME!

During the months of January through March,  Maui, Hawaii is home to one of the greatest whale watching spectacles on earth: A mass gathering of Humpback Whales in their winter breeding grounds!

I will be once again leading this five-day whale watching extravaganza February 15th-19th 2022! Included in your package is:

-Over 20 hours on the water with Maui's legendary Humpback Whales on a special low-to-the-water RIB boat led by myself, the Gone Whale Watching Team, and the best local guides on Maui

-Professional Photography Advice from myself and the Gone Whale Watching Crew

-Snorkel Opportunities at the island of Lānaʻ away from the crowds and tourists! Listen to the whales singing underwater as you explore this unique underwater oasis! Snorkel Gear included! (we do not swim with the whales as it is illegal on the island)

-Special commemorative t-shirt

-Free ticket to @gonewhalewatching San Diego

-Professional 4K "mini-documentary" of your adventure produced by myself and the GWW team

-A delicious welcome-dinner at one of Lahaina's best restaurants

Price is $1350 per person 
(airfare and accommodations not included)

Must call/text/email to book. 858 500 2568 or info@gonewhalewatching.com

50% Deposit due to reserve your spot. Remaining Balance due Feb. 1st 2022. Deposit is refundable through October 31st. After November 1st there is NO refunds.

This trip sold out in 48 hours for our first week of dates, so don’t delay and book your whale watching bucket-list trip of a lifetime!

node.text:
I would just be prepared for a whole bunch of orca content on this page the next few days! 

Some anecdotes to share about this encounter because there’s a LOT of bad information out there. First of all these are not Resident or Transient Killer Whales. This is not Washington State which has its own extreme regulations in response to the specific situation taking place in their local waters with two entirely different types of Orcas than the ones shown here. 

These whales belong to the Eastern Tropical Pacific population that’s not well understood. While we were in Mexican waters, I’d like to point out that this encounter would be completely legal under the United State’s Marine Mammal Protection Act as well even though our boat is moving in this clip (I’ll explain in a moment). The MMPA law states we simply can not “harass” dolphins and whales. This specific pod is famous for playing with boats, and specifically for “stern-wake riding” as you see pictured here. Abruptly stopping the boat and killing the motors would actually be substantially more dangerous to the whales in a situation like this than continuing at the same speed and heading because the boat suddenly stopping is not what the whales are anticipating the boat will do. Again the whales are “play chasing” US, not the other way around. For whatever reason this pod acts substantially more “dolphin-like” (they are dolphins after all!) than many other Orca pods. I would encourage you to check out the full video that’s going up on the @gonewhalewatching Facebook page shortly, and you’ll see how it’s clearly the whales pursing us, and not the other way around! The whales were quite the opposite of “harassed”, they were ENJOYING themselves! 

Even with all of that said, my crew and I are trained professionals that understand how to handle ourselves in a situation like this, and recognize which animals might want to play, and which want to be left alone, so if you’re ever on your own boat and spot a whale, it’s best to completely leave it alone. If you want to observe these creatures in the wild, book a reputable whale watching company that knows how to be sure the animals, and humans are kept safe!

node.text: Can you seriously imagine what it would be like to experience two wild Orcas coming right at you!?! Well this happened to us yesterday thanks in huge part to Jeff from @pacificbountysportfishing who had alerted me to orcas being in the area on Sunday! With a perfect weather window to go searching, we took @gonewhalewatching on a wild 80 mile adventure into Mexico that concluded with the holy grail of all sightings for us: Eastern Tropical Pacific Killer Whales! This is an unusually friendly group of Orcas that spent 5 hours playing with our boat, only taking a short break to hunt and kill a common dolphin! We’re going to try our luck at finding them again today, so stay tuned for more!

node.text:
Two years ago I had this crazy idea that I was going to start my own whale watching company. On August 26th, 2019 @gonewhalewatching ran its first official whale watch, and while I didn’t know at the time what the future would hold, nothing could have prepared me for what actually happened. First was the anxiety of starting a whale watching company from scratch in a saturated market. Wondering every day if anyone would even book my tours. Then came those first magical trips, those first reviews on Yelp, the slow but steady drip of business increasing, and then booming! Then came a new boat! A brand new boat, so new and shiny. I had never driven a truly new boat before, and I felt like i was on top of the world. Then covid happened and all of that doubt returned. Spring break was gone, summer was a fraction of what it was supposed to be, yet somehow the company not only survived, but thrived enough to add a second boat to our fleet. 

Looking back I realize that there was two things that made the last two years possible: the amazing animals that to this day consume my dreams and imagination, and my crew. From 14 hour film days that involve nap time on the bow, to karaoke parties, mid-trip shenanigans, and magical moments that will last a lifetime…I simply would not have made it through these two years without this amazing team (including the behind the scenes work Samantha still does in accounting!) by my side. So cheers to two years, and here’s to many more to come! 
#GoneWhaleWatching
